**EDIT:**

After reading [Clifford&#39;s answer][2], I also think that the best way to deal with `fseek()` and `ftell()` return values while calculating the size of a file is to write a dedicated function. However Clifford&#39;s good suggestion could not deal with the `size_t` data type (we need *a size* after all!), so I guess that the most practical approach in the end would be to use a pointer for storing the size of the file, and keep the return value of our dedicated function only for failures. Here is my contribution to Clifford&#39;s solution for a safe size calculator:

&lt;!-- language: c --&gt;

    int fsize (FILE * const file, size_t * const size) {
    
    	long int ftell_retval;
    
    	if (fseek(file, 0, SEEK_END) || (ftell_retval = ftell(file)) &lt; 0) {
    
    		/*  Error  */
    		*size = 0;
    		return 1;
    
    	}
    
    	*size = (size_t) ftell_retval;
    	return 0;
    
    }

So that when we need to know the length of a file we could simply do:

&lt;!-- language: c --&gt;

    size_t file_size;
    
